# Engineering Principles

Use these principles when evaluating proposals and implementations.

## Simplicity by default

- Default to the simplest design that meets correctness and reliability for current production needs.
- Treat added complexity as a last resort and justify it explicitly.

## Reliable and transparent behavior

- Prefer predictable behavior over cleverness.
- Make degraded or missing state explicit.
- Errors must be actionable.
- Avoid silent failure paths.

## Community contribution

- Keep the project easy to run locally.
- Keep setup and mental overhead low.

## Review posture

- Do not invent requirements or future scale needs.
- Push back on over-engineering.
- Call out weak error handling, unclear failures, and poor observability.
- Preserve important design context in code comments when that context would help future maintainers or agents amend the code safely.
